<h2>How do I <small>actually</small> annotate?</h2>
In the working file, we capture annotations in "2 columns" separated by the comma.
<div class="row">

<div class="span6">
<div class="alert alert-info">
<h3 align="center"><i>< cite >,< details ></i></h3>
</div>
</div>

<div class="span6">
<p><strong>< cite ></strong> would be provided for you already. E.g. <code>A00-1003==>P99-1029</code></p>
<p><strong>< details ></strong> is defined as below, respectively to the type of citation:</p>
</div>

</div>

<div class="row">
<div class="span6">
<div class="alert alert-success">
<h3>General <small>A single dash (or minus sign)</small></h3>
<p>A <strong>General</strong> citation is annotated with a single "dash". For example:</p>
<code>A00-1003==>P99-1029,<strong>-</strong></code>
<p>
<p>We annotate a cite as General when we cannot find a specific location for a cited information.</p>
</div>
</div>

<div class="span6">
<div class="alert alert-success">
<h3>Undetermined <small>A single question mark</small></h3>
<p>A <strong>Undetermined</strong> citation is annotated with a single "question mark". For example:</p>
<p><code>A00-1004==>J93-1006,<strong>?</strong></code></p>
<p>Example (in the cited paper):</p>
<pre class="prettyprint linenums">
189
190
191
based tagger by inferring rules...
</pre>
<p>The numbers you can see in this examples are actually page numbers in the original paper. So instead of having the actual content, you only have the page number, which is definitely not enough information for you to determine the type of citation.
</div>
</div>

</div>

<div class="row">
<div class="span12">
<div class="alert alert-success">
<h3>Specific <small>Numbers/Range/Exclamation</small></h3>
<p>A <strong>Specific</strong> citation is annotated numbers, ranges and/or exclamation marks. For example:</p>
<p>Single-line: <code>A00-1003==>P99-1029,<strong>85</strong></code> OR <code>A00-1003==>P99-1029,<strong>85-86</strong></code>. Note that we are capturing the entire sentence.</p>
<p>Multi-line: <code>A00-1004==>J93-2003,<strong>64-138</strong></code></p>
<p>Multi-locations: <code>A00-1004==>P91-1022,<strong>16!204-205</strong></code></p>
